lly and historically. In doing so, Bryson provides a case study of how people craft local identities out of disparate cultural elements and how these local identities transform over time in relation to larger historical changes-including the increasing presence of the Chinese state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBai (Chinese people)xReligion. 0aBuddhismzChinazDali Baizu ZizhizhouxHistory. 0aBuddhist goddesseszChinazDali Baizu ZizhizhouxHistory. 0aEthnicityxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 4aChina. 4aDali. 4aSouthwest China. 4aYunnan. 4aethnicity. 4afrontier. 4agender. 4agoddess. 4areligion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503600454zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600454423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600454.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles